\begin_layout Section
Legitimacy and the risk of the mechanisms triggering trade wars
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Throughout the analysis we have assumed away the possibility that countries
 that do not participate in the mechanisms might oppose it and retaliate
 against the participating countries.
 The EU's experience from 2012 that we outline in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:The-EU's-unilateral"

\end_inset

 shows that this danger needs to be taken very seriously.
 At the time many observers were concerned that the policy might trigger
 a 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "trade war"
target "https://www.dw.com/en/eu-emissions-policy-threatens-to-trigger-trade-war/a-16048424"

\end_inset

.
 For evaluating which mechanism should best be initiated, we need to take
 into account how each possible mechanism will affect the probability of
 a trade war.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It seems plausible that the more a mechanism contributes to the welfare
 of non-participants, the less likely it is that they will oppose it.
 Firstly, this is because they have less material incentive to try to cause
 the mechanism to disappear.
 Secondly, the mechanism will presumably be more legitimate if the participating
 countries allocate most of the money to GPGIs rather than keeping it for
 themselves (as the EU did in 2012).
 The results from section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Proportion-of-money"

\end_inset

 suggest that the MGF mechanisms raise for GPGIs a greater proportion of
 the the tax revenue collected than CORSIA+ does.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is another reason why the MGF mechanisms could have more legitimacy
 than CORSIA+: Allowing participating countries to decide how to allocate
 to GPGIs the money that they collect as taxes would accomodate the demands
 of several countries including Brasil and China, who 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "reportedly"
target "http://www.raes-montreal.org/html/en/body/events/lectures/2018/RAeSMB%20(2018.06.04)%20BeyondCORSIA.Lyle.pdf"

\end_inset

 in the context of the CORSIA negotiations reject the idea that the list
 of eligible offset standards should be determined by the ICAO Council and
 prefer that States be allowed to apply their own offset standards.
 According to 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "Andrew Murphy"
target "https://www.carbonbrief.org/corsia-un-plan-to-offset-growth-in-aviation-emissions-after-2020"

\end_inset

from the NGO Transport and Environment, who is an observer in the CORSIA
 negotiations: “The reason for China’s scepticism is that, as a point of
 principal, they don’t want to be told by a UN agency which offsets they
 have to use for their airlines.” 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These considerations thus all point in the direction of the MGF mechanisms
 having more legitimacy and incurring a lower probability of triggering
 a trade war.
\end_layout

