\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have found in the numerical simulations that the MGF with AEPMFs can
 achieve 29% more welfare than CORSIA+.
 Moreover, the outperformance of the MGF mechanism with AEPMFs over CORSIA+
 and the Simple MGF mechanism appears to be robust to relaxing the assumption
 that the retention rate parameter is chosen optimally for each mechanism.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One questionable assumption is that in the context of the mechanisms, the
 countries within each of the 12 regional blocks overcome their colletive
 action problems.
 This seems at first glance very implausible.
 However, in the context of the MGF mechanism with AEPMFs the gains from
 cooperation within each block might be particularly large, which presumably
 would make cooperation within each block more likely.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
To see this, consider for example the gains from cooperation for African
 countries that arise endogenously at the Nash equilibria described in section
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Results-for-the"

\end_inset

: All African countries most benefit from money going to the Global Fund
 Against AIDS, TB and Malaria.
 By participating and giving money to this GPGI, African countries can cause
 not just the tax money that they collect to go to this GPGI but also additional
 money that comes from the PMF with Global Fund Against AIDS, TB and Malaria,
 CEPI and Forest Carbon Partnership's Carbon Fund, to which the Middle East
 allocates all its tax revenue.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another questionable assumption is the absence of any foresight that has
 been implicit in the iterated best response algorithm that we have used.
 In all of the mechanisms that we have studied here the following holds:
 by participating, one decreases the incremental cost for the others to
 join.
 Thus foresight would weigh in favor of joining, since by doing so one can
 cause joining to be more attractive (and thus more likely) for others.
 Taking into account this effect would presumably improve the performance
 of all the three mechanisms to a similar extent.
 However, there is a further effect specific to the MGF with AEPMFs: By
